ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, a small piece of paraoxon-coated pakchoi was immersed in the solution containing the nanoreactors, and then when the fluorescence of the system no longer changed, the pakchoi was taken out and put into a new solution containing the nanoreactor to observe the fluorescence emission signal. As shown in Fig. 6b, the fluorescence emission of Fe-CDs/MOF-808 was gradually quenched by the addition of paraoxon-contaminated pakchoi until it was completely quenched after 4 min. As a control, the fluorescence of the system did not change in the presence of pakchoi without paraoxon. This result demonstrated that the OPs on the surface of pakchoi can indeed be degraded and detected by Fe-CDs/MOF-808 nanoreactor. It was also illustrated by the fluorescence spectra shown in Fig. 6c. To further confirm that the paraoxon on the surface of pakchoi has been completely degraded, the pakchoi was removed from the above solution at 5 min and added it to a new Fe-CDs/MOF-808 suspension, and we found no change in the fluorescence emission image and spectra of the suspension (Fig. 6b right and Fig. 6d). The results turn out that the paraoxon on the surface of pakchoi was completely degraded after Fe-CDs/MOF-808 treatment, and the surface did not contain paraoxon. At the same time, the developed Fe-CDs@MOF-808 was used to detect parathion in pakchoi (Table 1
                        ), and the results were consistent with those obtain by standard method (HPLC). Hence, it can be concluded that the nanoreactor can detoxify and detect paraoxon and parathion in real vegetable samples.
